WEBVTT

00:01.918 --> 00:03.160
<i>Tonight on</i>
The Curse of Oak Island...

00:03.253 --> 00:05.746
The Portuguese found signs
of gold here

00:05.839 --> 00:08.582
- and needed a place to hide it away.
- Wow.

00:08.666 --> 00:10.092
<i>CHARLES:
If that is indeed Shaft Six,</i>

00:10.251 --> 00:12.502
we know there's a tunnel
leading directly

00:12.587 --> 00:14.013
to the Money Pit.
You follow the tunnel,

00:14.172 --> 00:15.255
it's game on, then.

00:15.339 --> 00:16.923
<i>GARY:
All it takes is one good find.</i>

00:17.017 --> 00:18.258
What's that right there, Gary?

00:18.342 --> 00:19.342
Well, that's interesting.

00:19.427 --> 00:20.927
Might be a lid.

00:21.021 --> 00:22.095
There could be a chest in there.

00:22.188 --> 00:23.355
That's pretty amazing.

00:23.440 --> 00:24.848
<i>RICK:
You'll hold in your hand</i>

00:24.932 --> 00:26.692
<i>the irrefutable proof</i>

00:26.851 --> 00:28.360
that the story
of Oak Island is real.

00:31.022 --> 00:34.024
<i>NARRATOR: There is an
island in the North Atlantic</i>

00:34.117 --> 00:36.943
<i>where people
have been looking for</i>

00:37.037 --> 00:40.947
<i>an incredible treasure
for more than 200 years.</i>

00:41.032 --> 00:43.950
<i>So far, they have found
a stone slab</i>

00:44.044 --> 00:45.836
<i>with strange symbols
carved into it...</i>

00:47.288 --> 00:50.466
<i>man-made workings
that date to medieval times,</i>

00:50.550 --> 00:54.878
<i>and a lead cross
whose origin may be connected</i>

00:54.962 --> 00:56.129
<i>to the Knights Templar.</i>

00:56.214 --> 00:58.965
<i>To date, six men have died</i>

00:59.059 --> 01:01.885
<i>trying to solve the mystery.</i>

01:01.969 --> 01:06.890
<i>And according to legend,
one more will have to die</i>

01:06.983 --> 01:09.359
<i>before the treasure
can be found.</i>

01:14.407 --> 01:16.909
♪ ♪

01:21.414 --> 01:23.073
- CHARLES: Here we go!
- TERRY: Yup.

01:23.166 --> 01:26.993
- So, we're drilling here, HI-4.
- Yup.

01:27.078 --> 01:31.006
<i>NARRATOR: As another exciting
day begins on Oak Island,</i>

01:31.165 --> 01:35.252
<i>brothers Rick and Marty Lagina,
along with their team, believe</i>

01:35.336 --> 01:37.170
<i>that they may be on the verge</i>

01:37.263 --> 01:40.265
<i>of not only locating
the original Money Pit shaft...</i>

01:40.424 --> 01:44.937
- We could be starting to chase Shaft Six.
- Correct.

01:45.096 --> 01:46.939
<i>NARRATOR:
but also a vast treasure</i>

01:47.098 --> 01:48.849
<i>that people have been
attempting to recover</i>

01:48.942 --> 01:51.026
<i>for more than two centuries.</i>

01:52.278 --> 01:55.614
So, this hole will be drilled
right in the heart of Shaft Six.

01:55.698 --> 01:58.117
Yup. If that is
indeed Shaft Six,

01:58.276 --> 02:00.443
we know at 118 feet,

02:00.537 --> 02:02.871
there's a tunnel
going off of that,

02:02.956 --> 02:05.532
- leading directly to the Money Pit.
- Right.

02:05.625 --> 02:07.868
<i>CHARLES:
You got wood.</i>

02:07.961 --> 02:10.203
Yeah, we've got some stacked
timbers there, it looks like.

02:10.296 --> 02:12.539
<i>NARRATOR: One week
ago, while drilling a borehole</i>

02:12.623 --> 02:16.051
<i>within their strategic grid,
known as G-2...</i>

02:16.210 --> 02:19.471
- That says to me, probably the shaft.
- I would say.

02:19.630 --> 02:21.715
<i>NARRATOR:
at depth of 80 to 90 feet,</i>

02:21.799 --> 02:25.719
<i>the team obtained evidence
of a wall believed to be part</i>

02:25.812 --> 02:28.305
<i>of a structure
simply known as "Shaft Six."</i>

02:28.398 --> 02:29.806
TERRY:
Definitely not circular saw.

02:29.899 --> 02:32.142
- This is relatively old.
- Yeah.

02:33.319 --> 02:37.147
<i>NARRATOR: Constructed
by searchers in 1861,</i>

02:37.231 --> 02:41.910
<i>this 118-foot-deep shaft
features a lateral tunnel</i>

02:42.069 --> 02:44.496
<i>that not only connects
to the original Money Pit,</i>

02:44.581 --> 02:47.824
<i>but is also believed
to contain a debris field</i>

02:47.909 --> 02:51.661
<i>full of valuables that resulted
from a catastrophic collapse</i>

02:51.754 --> 02:53.797
<i>that occurred
during its construction.</i>

02:55.008 --> 02:57.593
We got a core coming!

02:57.677 --> 03:00.837
<i>NARRATOR: Now, as the
team drills Borehole HI-4,</i>

03:00.930 --> 03:03.098
<i>which sets just
12-and-a-half feet</i>

03:03.183 --> 03:04.683
<i>from Borehole G-2...</i>

03:04.842 --> 03:06.676
Sixty-nine.

03:06.769 --> 03:09.429
- 59 to 69, coming at us, Charles.
- Yup.

03:09.513 --> 03:12.265
<i>NARRATOR: it is their
hope to recover solid evidence</i>

03:12.358 --> 03:15.101
<i>of the gold and silver that
they've recently detected</i>

03:15.195 --> 03:18.363
<i>from water sample tests
across the Money Pit area.</i>

03:18.522 --> 03:22.525
<i>If they are successful,
Rick, Marty and the team</i>

03:22.619 --> 03:25.946
<i>will dig a ten-foot-wide
steel-cased shaft here</i>

03:26.030 --> 03:29.291
<i>to intercept the Shaft Six
tunnel and recover the riches</i>

03:29.450 --> 03:31.793
<i>believed to lie within it.</i>

03:31.878 --> 03:35.372
<i>RICK: I've always believed
that finding Shaft Six is the way</i>

03:35.456 --> 03:39.042
<i>to really decide whether or not
the Money Pit can be found.</i>

03:39.126 --> 03:43.388
Shaft Six was sunk to 118 feet,
a tunnel driven 18 feet.

03:43.547 --> 03:45.557
We don't know
the cardinal direction of that.

03:45.716 --> 03:47.893
<i>So, delineate it,</i>

03:48.052 --> 03:50.729
<i>see if the measurements
of the shaft work, and then,</i>

03:50.813 --> 03:53.982
<i>try to determine
the orientation of the shaft.</i>

03:54.141 --> 03:55.642
What's the good word, Adam?

03:55.735 --> 03:58.403
- 75.
- TERRY: Thanks, Adam.

03:58.562 --> 04:00.489
69 to 75.

04:04.077 --> 04:05.827
- Here we go.
- Yup.

04:07.914 --> 04:09.998
Charles, we have wood.

04:12.326 --> 04:14.744
Maybe this will be the stacked
timbers we've been looking for.

04:14.837 --> 04:19.332
Yup, that's apparently
stacked timbers.

04:19.425 --> 04:22.928
Gives me a good indication
of potentially a, uh, shaft.

04:23.087 --> 04:25.338
Could be we're clipping
the edge of a shaft.

04:25.423 --> 04:26.848
That's what I'm thinking.

04:26.933 --> 04:28.758
<i>NARRATOR:
Evidence of a shaft</i>

04:28.851 --> 04:32.929
<i>found some 70 feet deep
in Borehole HI-4?</i>

04:33.014 --> 04:36.433
<i>Has the team possibly found
a second wall of Shaft Six?</i>

04:36.526 --> 04:38.860
It could be a corner piece
right there.

04:38.945 --> 04:40.946
<i>NARRATOR: If so, then
they might not only be able</i>

04:41.030 --> 04:43.857
<i>to determine the orientation
of the shaft,</i>

04:43.941 --> 04:47.744
<i>but also the precise location
of the original Money Pit.</i>

04:48.871 --> 04:50.455
Hey, Rick.

04:50.614 --> 04:51.957
<i>NARRATOR:
Arriving for an update</i>

04:52.116 --> 04:53.199
<i>on the morning's
drilling progress</i>

04:53.293 --> 04:56.712
<i>are Rick Lagina,
surveyor Steve Guptill</i>

04:56.796 --> 04:59.214
<i>and Oak Island
historian Doug Crowell.</i>

04:59.373 --> 05:00.882
What have we got?

05:00.967 --> 05:05.962
HI-4 is in the southeast
quadrant of our shaft.

05:06.047 --> 05:08.974
We've come through
a substantial portion

05:09.058 --> 05:11.893
of the wall from about,
what was that?

05:11.978 --> 05:13.970
- 71?
- 71 to...

05:14.055 --> 05:15.480
To about 75 feet.

05:15.565 --> 05:17.399
What we feel was

05:17.483 --> 05:21.153
the outside wall of,
hopefully, Shaft Six.

05:21.312 --> 05:25.324
If we find the tunnel
associated with that,

05:25.483 --> 05:28.827
you'll hold in your hand
the irrefutable proof

05:28.986 --> 05:34.166
that the story
of Oak Island is real.

05:34.325 --> 05:36.752
Is defined by one thing
and one thing only:

05:36.911 --> 05:38.420
hold the evidence in your hand.

05:38.579 --> 05:41.164
Find the one thing.
That's success.

05:41.248 --> 05:43.833
<i>Look, now we have
a proper orientation,</i>

05:43.926 --> 05:46.503
<i>and one could make
a very good case</i>

05:46.596 --> 05:48.922
<i>that the Money Pit--
It's certainly close.</i>

05:49.015 --> 05:50.515
It helps us with our,

05:50.674 --> 05:52.851
you know, "where do we put
a caisson?" decision.

05:52.935 --> 05:55.020
- Yup.
- Always.

05:55.104 --> 05:57.680
Keep after it. Keep up
the good work. Good luck, guys.

05:57.774 --> 05:59.858
- We'll do our best. Thank you.
- Thank you. - Talk to you later.

06:00.017 --> 06:02.185
<i>NARRATOR: As efforts
to reach the tunnel</i>

06:02.269 --> 06:04.104
<i>connected to Shaft Six continue</i>

06:04.197 --> 06:07.107
<i>at the Money Pit,
later that afternoon...</i>

06:07.191 --> 06:09.192
- Does that stink!
- Yeah.

06:09.285 --> 06:12.445
<i>NARRATOR: Marty Lagina joins
Doug Crowell,</i>

06:12.530 --> 06:14.706
<i>metal detection expert
Gary Drayton,</i>

06:14.865 --> 06:17.283
<i>and heavy equipment
operator Billy Gerhardt</i>

06:17.377 --> 06:20.128
<i>as they continue excavating
at the southernmost region</i>

06:20.287 --> 06:22.297
<i>of the triangle-shaped swamp.</i>

06:22.382 --> 06:24.216
Get me up to speed.
What's going on here?

06:24.375 --> 06:25.634
We're finding wood.

06:25.793 --> 06:27.135
The wood that we're finding

06:27.294 --> 06:28.637
is really,
really interesting, Marty.

06:28.796 --> 06:30.130
Mm-hmm. You found any metal?

06:30.223 --> 06:31.807
No, no metal yet.

06:34.051 --> 06:35.885
We're digging deep out here,

06:35.970 --> 06:37.554
and we're working our way

06:37.638 --> 06:39.064
towards where we found
that piece of wood

06:39.148 --> 06:41.733
- dated to 600, 700 AD.
- Mm-hmm.

06:41.818 --> 06:44.394
<i>NARRATOR:
Over the past two weeks,</i>

06:44.478 --> 06:47.072
<i>the Oak Island team has made
numerous discoveries</i>

06:47.156 --> 06:49.232
<i>in this area near
the western end</i>

06:49.325 --> 06:50.733
<i>of the massive
stone ship's wharf,</i>

06:50.818 --> 06:53.662
<i>which may be more than
500 years old</i>

06:53.821 --> 06:56.573
<i>and also of Portuguese origin.</i>

06:56.657 --> 07:00.493
<i>These finds include
a mysterious tree stump,</i>

07:00.578 --> 07:04.080
<i>offering more evidence that
the swamp was once dry land,</i>

07:04.165 --> 07:08.001
<i>wooden survey stakes
and hand-hewn planks</i>

07:08.085 --> 07:11.004
<i>that may be connected
to the ancient wharf.</i>

07:11.088 --> 07:14.674
<i>It was in this same area that,
one year ago,</i>

07:14.758 --> 07:17.760
<i>the team recovered a potential
piece of a ship's railing</i>

07:17.845 --> 07:21.773
<i>that was carbon-dated
to the seventh century AD,</i>

07:21.932 --> 07:26.111
<i>and also where they detected
a massive, 200-foot-long</i>

07:26.195 --> 07:28.605
<i>ship-shaped anomaly
using seismic scanning</i>

07:28.689 --> 07:30.365
<i>three years ago.</i>

07:30.450 --> 07:31.867
JEREMY:
It's very unusual.

07:32.026 --> 07:33.276
MARTY:
Let's not just dork around it.

07:33.360 --> 07:35.778
- Yeah.
- Would it be S-H-I-P?

07:35.863 --> 07:38.531
Would that be
what everybody's thinking?

07:38.624 --> 07:41.868
What do you think about
having him go down three feet?

07:41.952 --> 07:45.714
Uh, yeah. I'd like to do that
because along this bank...

07:45.873 --> 07:47.549
- Mm-hmm.
- Where the road is here,

07:47.708 --> 07:49.542
we've found a heck of a lot

07:49.635 --> 07:52.545
of wharf pins, ship's spikes.

07:52.638 --> 07:54.806
- Yeah.
- Yeah. I wouldn't mind going deeper.

07:57.977 --> 07:59.552
So, while you're here,

07:59.645 --> 08:01.730
here's a thought, Billy.
It won't take too long

08:01.814 --> 08:04.474
as long as this machine's
so nicely situated.

08:04.567 --> 08:06.142
Come by, take, like,
about a foot of that sand,

08:06.235 --> 08:07.810
put it to the side,
metal detect.

08:07.895 --> 08:10.906
Take another foot, another foot,
get down maybe four feet

08:10.990 --> 08:12.324
just to see if there's something
in that sand.

08:12.408 --> 08:15.577
- Yeah, now I'm definitely for that.
- Okay. Thank you.

08:15.661 --> 08:18.580
- Yeah, we're going to do it, Gary.
- GARY: Yeah.

08:22.502 --> 08:24.794
- Should be something in there.
- Yeah, should be something.

08:26.339 --> 08:29.257
<i>MARTY: One thing that
is just totally inexplicable</i>

08:29.416 --> 08:31.918
<i>was a piece of wood carbon-dated</i>

08:32.011 --> 08:36.673
twice, uh, to AD 700.

08:36.757 --> 08:40.593
Okay, well, that's...
that's an outlier.

08:40.686 --> 08:44.439
<i>So, because it's such an outlier
and so different,</i>

08:44.598 --> 08:46.024
<i>we need to do more searching.</i>

08:49.019 --> 08:50.687
(clattering)

08:50.780 --> 08:52.781
Whoa. Yeah, what's that, Gary?

08:52.865 --> 08:54.941
GARY:
Let's have a look. Wow.

08:55.034 --> 08:57.110
That is a big piece, isn't it?

08:57.203 --> 08:58.453
MARTY:
Oh, baby!

09:04.785 --> 09:07.287
That looks like it was cut.

09:07.371 --> 09:10.540
<i>NARRATOR: Near the southern
edge of the triangle-shaped swamp,</i>

09:10.624 --> 09:12.634
<i>Marty Lagina
and members of the team</i>

09:12.718 --> 09:14.877
<i>have just unearthed
a potentially important clue.</i>

09:14.962 --> 09:17.964
- It looks like one of the old survey stakes.
- Oh.

09:18.048 --> 09:19.808
Hey, that might be.
It might have been cut.

09:19.892 --> 09:23.895
Yeah. What do you think
it is, Marty?

09:23.980 --> 09:26.982
It looks, sort of, Gary,
like the stakes they used

09:27.066 --> 09:28.975
- that would laid out the road.
- Yeah.

09:29.059 --> 09:30.235
So, maybe back to the 1600s.

09:30.319 --> 09:31.486
- It looks sort of like that.
- Yeah.

09:31.571 --> 09:35.323
<i>NARRATOR:
Another possible survey stake?</i>

09:35.408 --> 09:38.493
<i>Could it be connected to
the massive stone ship's wharf</i>

09:38.578 --> 09:42.247
<i>which sets just east
of this location in the swamp?</i>

09:42.331 --> 09:45.074
<i>Or could it be related
in some way</i>

09:45.159 --> 09:47.335
<i>to the 200-foot-long
anomaly detected</i>

09:47.420 --> 09:51.080
<i>by seismic scanning in 2018?</i>

09:51.165 --> 09:54.884
<i>One resembling the size
and shape of a ship?</i>

10:03.352 --> 10:05.678
Come on. Just one good signal.

10:05.763 --> 10:07.263
What's that right there, Gary?

10:07.348 --> 10:09.774
- What?
- That weird thing on the side.

10:12.945 --> 10:14.946
That's planking.

10:16.190 --> 10:19.034
Planking or decking or...

10:19.118 --> 10:22.704
But that looks very interesting.

10:22.788 --> 10:24.956
- Got that beveled edge on it.
- Yeah.

10:25.041 --> 10:26.541
Sure looks like...

10:26.700 --> 10:30.378
decking? Wooden decking

10:30.463 --> 10:32.288
- or planking to me.
- Yeah.

10:32.373 --> 10:34.707
<i>NARRATOR:
Wooden deck planking?</i>

10:34.792 --> 10:36.801
<i>Could Gary Drayton be correct</i>

10:36.960 --> 10:38.887
<i>that the team has
just found more evidence</i>

10:39.046 --> 10:40.972
<i>of a ship in the swamp?</i>

10:41.131 --> 10:44.643
<i>If so, might it also be
connected to the piece</i>

10:44.802 --> 10:47.303
<i>of believed ship's railing
