10:47.388 --> 10:51.224
<i>that dated to as early
as the seventh century AD?</i>

10:51.308 --> 10:54.903
<i>MARTY: I am surprised at
how much stuff is in that swamp.</i>

10:55.062 --> 10:58.448
Interesting things. I mean,
the paved area, the stone road.

10:59.825 --> 11:03.411
All the artifacts in
the southeast corner, and now,

11:03.496 --> 11:06.239
as we dig along the beach,
all kinds of pieces of wood.

11:06.323 --> 11:08.574
<i>Potentially significant
pieces of wood.</i>

11:08.668 --> 11:11.160
- Yeah. That's shaped wood for sure.
- GARY: Yeah.

11:11.245 --> 11:13.838
MARTY: "What's it mean?"
is the question.

11:13.923 --> 11:14.997
After we clean it up,
we might have a better idea

11:15.091 --> 11:16.675
- of what it actually is.
- Yeah.

11:16.834 --> 11:20.178
<i>MARTY:
All right, let's keep digging.</i>

11:25.092 --> 11:27.102
<i>NARRATOR:
The following morning,</i>

11:27.186 --> 11:29.429
<i>while operations continue
at the swamp...</i>

11:29.513 --> 11:31.597
(whoops)

11:31.682 --> 11:33.775
<i>NARRATOR:
and in the Money Pit area...</i>

11:33.934 --> 11:36.936
<i>RICK: Doug has come up with
a presentation which I find</i>

11:37.020 --> 11:38.438
intriguing, to say the least.

11:38.522 --> 11:41.282
<i>NARRATOR:
in the war room, Rick Lagina</i>

11:41.367 --> 11:44.202
<i>has gathered members of the team
to hear a presentation</i>

11:44.361 --> 11:46.362
<i>by Doug Crowell
that he has prepared</i>

11:46.447 --> 11:49.282
<i>regarding some
of their recent discoveries.</i>

11:49.366 --> 11:52.627
What encapsulates Oak Island
and the search for answers here,

11:52.786 --> 11:55.621
of course, is the "who, what,
where, when, why and how."

11:55.715 --> 12:00.051
Well, Doug has taken it upon
himself to address the "who."

12:00.136 --> 12:03.304
So, Doug, we will
turn it over to you, please.

12:03.389 --> 12:05.631
Yes, well, so,
what really kicked off

12:05.716 --> 12:07.633
this preliminary report

12:07.727 --> 12:11.721
is the finding of these
two round stones on the island.

12:11.805 --> 12:13.973
What was really interesting
about these is,

12:14.057 --> 12:16.067
these are not likely native
to Nova Scotia.

12:18.562 --> 12:20.146
GARY:
Whoa! Look at that!

12:20.230 --> 12:23.158
- It's a round shot!
- RICK: Wow.

12:23.242 --> 12:25.076
<i>NARRATOR:
Two months ago,</i>

12:25.161 --> 12:27.653
<i>while investigating
a possible ancient pathway</i>

12:27.747 --> 12:30.656
<i>between the swamp
and the Money Pit on Lot 16,</i>

12:30.741 --> 12:32.742
<i>Rick and Gary Drayton</i>

12:32.826 --> 12:36.746
<i>discovered a stone shot
or small cannonball.</i>

12:36.830 --> 12:40.500
<i>Incredibly, it was not only
nearly identical</i>

12:40.584 --> 12:44.921
<i>to one excavated
from the Money Pit in 2019,</i>

12:45.005 --> 12:47.340
<i>but when the team
had them analyzed</i>

12:47.424 --> 12:52.020
<i>by geology professor Dr. Robert
Raeside, in his opinion,</i>

12:52.179 --> 12:55.932
<i>one of the likely places
they originated was the Azores,</i>

12:56.016 --> 12:58.443
<i>a group of islands in Portugal.</i>

12:58.527 --> 13:01.604
These would classify as what
they'd call "two pounders".

13:01.697 --> 13:04.857
So, they'd be shot out
of a-a deck gun

13:04.950 --> 13:07.693
or a swivel gun, a rail gun
off the side of a ship.

13:07.778 --> 13:10.446
- Wow.
- And the Portuguese were the very first

13:10.531 --> 13:12.707
to put cannon
on board their ships.

13:12.792 --> 13:18.371
The stone shot came into play
around the early 1400s,

13:18.464 --> 13:21.216
and dwindled out of...
out of use in the mid-1600s.

13:21.300 --> 13:24.803
So, if these were from a ship

13:24.887 --> 13:27.463
or individuals
that visited Oak Island,

