<i>NARRATOR:
geologist Terry Matheson</i>

26:29.412 --> 26:32.006
<i>and Oak Island historian
Charles Barkhouse</i>

26:32.090 --> 26:34.916
<i>are supervising
the drilling operation</i>

26:35.010 --> 26:40.347
<i>in the team's new borehole on
their strategic grid-- F.25-4.</i>

26:40.432 --> 26:43.759
<i>A borehole that they hope
will intercept a tunnel</i>

26:43.852 --> 26:47.262
<i>some 118 feet deep
that is believed</i>

26:47.355 --> 26:49.348
<i>to contain a debris field
of treasure</i>

26:49.432 --> 26:52.184
<i>connected
to the original Money Pit.</i>

26:52.277 --> 26:55.029
TERRY: We're only about
a foot away from F-4 there.

26:55.188 --> 26:58.115
If that is indeed Shaft Six and
the tunnel coming off of that,

26:58.199 --> 27:00.692
maybe that could account
for the high

27:00.785 --> 27:03.945
gold and silver readings
we're getting in F-4.

27:04.030 --> 27:06.290
Exactly.
Part of the smashed-up treasure

27:06.374 --> 27:08.292
or a vault
that has fallen and shot

27:08.451 --> 27:09.793
- into the Shaft Six tunnel.
- Yeah.

27:09.952 --> 27:11.453
<i>MARTY:
There could be a tunnel</i>

27:11.537 --> 27:12.871
<i>between the shaft
and the Money Pit area.</i>

27:12.955 --> 27:14.632
<i>So, we're looking for it.</i>

27:14.791 --> 27:17.217
<i>And the collapse
of the Money Pit.</i>

27:17.377 --> 27:22.214
<i>The water samples show the most
gold and silver right there, so,</i>

27:22.307 --> 27:24.725
we think we're zeroing in
on potentially at least part

27:24.809 --> 27:26.644
of the treasure.

27:26.728 --> 27:28.979
- CHARLES: We got another core coming.
- Yup.

27:30.890 --> 27:32.891
- 119.
- 119.

27:32.975 --> 27:34.151
Yup.

27:36.988 --> 27:40.240
Look at this, Charles.
This is really mixed up.

27:40.325 --> 27:43.068
In terms of constituents,
it's all till.

27:43.161 --> 27:44.912
But look at the wood and chips
and chunks through it.

27:45.071 --> 27:46.655
- Yeah.
- That's not at the periphery or the outside.

27:46.748 --> 27:48.156
It's right in the core
and center.

27:48.249 --> 27:51.910
This is definitely
clumps and chunks

27:52.003 --> 27:56.590
of material that
was dug out, mixed with clumps

27:56.749 --> 27:59.835
of sticks and twigs that
fell in between the clumps.

27:59.919 --> 28:03.097
It's partially backfill
and partially

28:03.181 --> 28:05.015
dug material.

28:05.174 --> 28:08.769
So... we did not
intersect a tunnel.

28:08.928 --> 28:12.681
That doesn't mean it's not
there. We just didn't hit it.

28:12.765 --> 28:14.191
We just didn't hit it.
That's right.

28:15.527 --> 28:19.780
<i>NARRATOR: Having now
reached a depth of nearly 120 feet,</i>

28:19.939 --> 28:22.941
<i>and finding no hard evidence
of the Shaft Six tunnel</i>

28:23.034 --> 28:25.369
<i>nor the treasure it is
believed to contain,</i>

28:25.453 --> 28:29.114
<i>it appears that the team
has missed their target.</i>

28:29.207 --> 28:32.376
<i>However, since they have
discovered high concentrations</i>

28:32.535 --> 28:36.630
<i>of both silver and gold
in nearby Borehole F-4</i>

28:36.789 --> 28:40.467
<i>through water testing, they may
not have missed by much.</i>

28:40.626 --> 28:43.554
<i>And when they begin digging
ten-foot-wide caissons</i>

28:43.638 --> 28:46.140
<i>in the area just
a few short weeks from now,</i>

28:46.299 --> 28:48.300
<i>perhaps the ultimate discovery</i>

28:48.393 --> 28:51.636
<i>connected to Shaft Six
still awaits them.</i>

28:51.721 --> 28:54.231
<i>RICK: Look, it's a process,
all right? It's incremental.</i>

28:54.390 --> 28:56.641
<i>And I think we're going
to stay the course and</i>

28:56.735 --> 28:59.653
continue to drill the grid,
and hopefully,

28:59.812 --> 29:00.979
<i>from that work, we'll be able</i>

29:01.072 --> 29:03.148
<i>to ascertain exactly
where the spots are</i>

29:03.241 --> 29:06.151
<i>to put large cans
to solve this thing.</i>

29:06.244 --> 29:08.987
TERRY: At least we
know exactly where it isn't.

29:09.071 --> 29:11.165
So, we can move over
and see if we hit it

29:11.324 --> 29:13.917
- just a little further to the east or west.
- Okay.

29:14.002 --> 29:15.836
<i>TERRY:
Lots of good information.</i>

29:19.090 --> 29:21.258
<i>NARRATOR:
While Terry Matheson concludes</i>

29:21.342 --> 29:25.086
<i>the drilling operation
in Borehole F.25-4...</i>

29:25.171 --> 29:27.506
<i>BILLY: We're getting down into
this more important zone,</i>

29:27.590 --> 29:29.424
I think. You know,
every time we move ahead,

29:29.509 --> 29:31.351
I'm a little more confident
that we might find

29:31.511 --> 29:34.354
- more pieces related to what we found last year.
- Yeah. Yeah.

29:34.439 --> 29:37.098
<i>NARRATOR: Charles Barkhouse
joins Gary Drayton</i>

29:37.183 --> 29:39.860
<i>and other members of the team
to look for more evidence</i>

29:40.019 --> 29:43.355
<i>of a possible buried ship,
and hopefully valuables,</i>

29:43.439 --> 29:46.024
<i>near the southern edge
of the swamp.</i>

29:46.108 --> 29:48.035
But all it takes, mate,
is one good find.

29:48.194 --> 29:49.536
- Yup, that's it.
- And let's get that good find today.

29:49.695 --> 29:51.205
CHARLES:
Laird and I

29:51.289 --> 29:53.207
are gonna go over, and
we'll observe as you're digging.

29:53.366 --> 29:55.626
Just in case we see something
that you're pulling up,

29:55.710 --> 29:57.202
- we can warn these guys.
- GARY: All right, mate.

29:57.295 --> 29:58.453
I'll get stuck in.

29:58.546 --> 30:01.790
<i>RICK: We're finding
a plethora of items,</i>

30:01.874 --> 30:04.218
<i>what we deem
to be nautical finds.</i>

30:04.377 --> 30:07.212
<i>There's certainly some
strange goings-on in the swamp,</i>

30:07.305 --> 30:11.058
and I don't think we're anywhere
near, uh, the finality of it.

30:11.142 --> 30:14.803
GARY: All right, mate. We
need a ship's bell, don't we?

30:14.887 --> 30:17.064
- Yeah.
- Is that a...?

30:17.148 --> 30:19.900
Look! That's a...

30:20.059 --> 30:22.069
Is that a piece of planking?

30:22.153 --> 30:23.737
Looks like it's cut, as well.

30:23.822 --> 30:25.897
It does. Yup.

30:25.990 --> 30:27.574
- It's worth saving and cleaning up.
- Yeah.

30:27.659 --> 30:29.493
Hey, you know what
it reminds me of?

30:29.652 --> 30:30.569
- Could be...
- You see that curve?

30:30.653 --> 30:33.071
It reminds me of a barrel stave.

30:33.155 --> 30:34.498
Yeah.

30:34.657 --> 30:35.657
<i>NARRATOR:
A possible barrel stave?</i>

30:35.750 --> 30:37.158
This is one right here, too.

30:37.252 --> 30:39.503
I think
we've found a barrel here.

30:39.662 --> 30:41.580
<i>NARRATOR:
Over the past year,</i>

30:41.664 --> 30:44.091
<i>the team has found pieces
of cargo barrels</i>

30:44.175 --> 30:48.003
<i>in the swamp that date back
500 years or more,</i>

30:48.096 --> 30:50.922
<i>not only near
the cobblestone pathway,</i>

30:51.015 --> 30:53.267
<i>which may be heading
toward the Money Pit,</i>

30:53.426 --> 30:55.343
<i>but also near the eastern side</i>

30:55.436 --> 30:57.938
<i>of the massive stone
ship's wharf.</i>

30:58.097 --> 31:02.183
<i>A ship's wharf that may also
date back at least 500 years</i>

31:02.277 --> 31:05.529
<i>and be of Portuguese origin.</i>

31:05.613 --> 31:07.439
Would be curious to see if this
matches up with the others.

31:07.523 --> 31:10.367
<i>NARRATOR: Could this
potential piece of a barrel,</i>

31:10.451 --> 31:12.861
<i>found in the area
where the team has also</i>

31:12.954 --> 31:14.788
<i>recently unearthed
parts of a ship,</i>

31:14.873 --> 31:18.033
<i>be connected
and provide more evidence</i>

31:18.117 --> 31:21.879
<i>of an ancient operation to
unload cargo onto Oak Island?</i>

31:22.038 --> 31:23.797
- Well, we'll save it.
- GARY: Okay.

31:26.208 --> 31:28.710
All right, mate.
Better get out of the way.

31:28.803 --> 31:31.546
Billy Buckets is coming in.

31:31.639 --> 31:34.466
BILLY:
It may be nothing,

31:34.559 --> 31:36.468
but when I flick the bucket,
just come ahead,

31:36.561 --> 31:38.228
just come right ahead
in front of the bucket.

31:38.387 --> 31:40.814
There's a small
little pointy piece.

31:40.899 --> 31:42.149
- This?
- Yeah.

31:42.233 --> 31:43.567
GARY:
Oh, wow.

31:43.651 --> 31:46.320
<i>Well, that's interesting.
Look at that, Scott.</i>

31:50.241 --> 31:51.575
- Look at that, Scott.
- That's a nice piece, Gary.

31:51.659 --> 31:53.160
GARY: I mean, yeah,
you can definitely tell

31:53.244 --> 31:54.402
that's not natural.
That's been shaped like that.

31:54.487 --> 31:57.906
- No. For sure.
- Laird!

31:57.990 --> 32:01.168
<i>NARRATOR: Near the southern
edge of the Oak Island swamp,</i>

32:01.252 --> 32:03.244
<i>metal detection expert
Gary Drayton</i>

32:03.329 --> 32:06.331
<i>along with Billy Gerhardt
and other members of the team</i>

32:06.424 --> 32:10.093
<i>have just made another
potentially critical discovery.</i>

32:11.179 --> 32:13.430
The archaeologist is here.

32:13.514 --> 32:15.349
Oh. What do you have?

32:15.433 --> 32:17.935
Well, we don't know, mate.
Some kind of wooden plug.

32:18.019 --> 32:20.604
- Huh.
- Or a pin.

32:20.763 --> 32:23.848
Yeah. You can see
it's square here,

32:23.933 --> 32:25.850
and then someone's
carefully tapered it.

32:25.935 --> 32:29.279
Yeah. It's-it's just got
a nautical feel to it.

32:29.438 --> 32:30.697
Yeah.

32:30.856 --> 32:34.284
- And you see the beveled edges on the side?
- Yup.

32:34.443 --> 32:36.870
GARY: I mean, if we're
finding ship's parts,

32:37.029 --> 32:38.363
that would be well at home.

32:38.456 --> 32:39.873
Yeah, for sure.

32:39.958 --> 32:42.534
<i>NARRATOR:
A possible ship's pin found</i>

32:42.618 --> 32:44.795
<i>near the southern edge
of the swamp?</i>

32:44.954 --> 32:48.715
<i>Dating back prior to the
14th century in Europe,</i>

32:48.874 --> 32:51.885
<i>ship's pins, or belaying pins,</i>

32:51.970 --> 32:54.137
<i>were made of either
metal or wood</i>

32:54.222 --> 32:56.223
<i>and were used to secure
the rigging lines</i>

32:56.382 --> 32:58.558
<i>for raising and lowering sails,</i>

32:58.718 --> 33:01.895
<i>as well as for docking ships.</i>

33:01.980 --> 33:04.222
SCOTT: Then there's
potential for that to be quite old.

33:04.315 --> 33:06.316
Yup, yup.

33:06.475 --> 33:08.235
<i>NARRATOR:
Because wooden belaying pins</i>

33:08.394 --> 33:11.738
<i>were replaced by metal cleats
by the 19th century,</i>

33:11.897 --> 33:15.909
<i>is it possible the team has
just discovered more evidence</i>

33:15.994 --> 33:19.329
<i>of an ancient ship
buried in the swamp?</i>

33:19.488 --> 33:22.165
GARY: That's the good
thing about the swamp.

33:22.250 --> 33:25.419
It might be stinky,
but it saves all the good stuff.

33:25.578 --> 33:27.587
You know, it makes you wonder
what else is in there, right?

33:27.672 --> 33:29.923
- GARY: Yeah.
- Or what-what we could be missing.

33:30.008 --> 33:32.009
GARY:
Yeah.

33:32.168 --> 33:33.427
CHARLES: All right.
Let's get back to it.

33:33.586 --> 33:34.761
- Thanks, Laird.
- Thank you.

33:34.920 --> 33:37.347
(engine starts)

33:43.345 --> 33:45.772
I don't know about that.
Looks more like bark.

33:45.857 --> 33:48.442
- Yeah.
- I think we're barking up the wrong tree with that one.

34:01.539 --> 34:03.623
What is this?

34:05.117 --> 34:07.202
That's a pretty smooth piece
of wood right there.

34:07.295 --> 34:10.371
GARY:
Oh, wow. It's interesting. Look.

34:10.465 --> 34:12.791
That looks like it was cut.

34:12.884 --> 34:17.137
But why would anybody ever
cut something in that way?

34:17.221 --> 34:18.889
GARY:
It stood out, didn't it?

34:19.048 --> 34:20.057
Hey, Laird!

34:20.216 --> 34:22.142
- They're calling you in, Laird.
- Yeah.

34:24.395 --> 34:26.229
What do you got?

34:26.388 --> 34:27.731
We're hoping
you can tell us, mate.

34:27.890 --> 34:29.808
First impression:
it looks like it's a...

34:29.892 --> 34:32.069
a knot broken out
of a trunk of a tree.

34:32.228 --> 34:33.737
CHARLES:
Wow.

34:33.896 --> 34:35.396
SCOTT:
But it's clearly been cut.

34:35.490 --> 34:38.900
You ever seen anything
like that?

34:38.993 --> 34:42.737
No. It almost looks carved.

34:42.822 --> 34:45.573
Yeah. It looks like it's been
cut on the top and the bottom.

34:45.666 --> 34:47.918
Yeah. Could it be
part of a tool?

34:48.077 --> 34:49.911
- LAIRD: Could well be.
- GARY: Yeah.

34:50.004 --> 34:51.922
Almost reminds me of, like,

34:52.081 --> 34:54.424
that wooden T square
we found in the swamp.

34:54.583 --> 34:57.085
- CHARLES: Oh, yeah.
- LAIRD: Yeah.

34:57.169 --> 35:00.839
- RICK: Check this out.
- Oh, God. Wow.

35:00.932 --> 35:04.259
<i>NARRATOR: Last year,
after discovering the pieces</i>

35:04.343 --> 35:06.177
<i>of cargo barrels
along the cobblestone path</i>

35:06.270 --> 35:09.180
<i>near the eastern border
of the swamp,</i>

35:09.265 --> 35:11.608
<i>Rick Lagina and members
of the team</i>

35:11.767 --> 35:14.194
<i>found what they believe
to be a mason's wooden</i>

35:14.353 --> 35:16.446
<i>T square measuring tool.</i>

35:16.531 --> 35:21.192
<i>Okay. We're gonna look
at the wood mason's tool.</i>

35:21.285 --> 35:23.194
<i>NARRATOR:
When they had it carbon-dated,</i>

35:23.287 --> 35:25.280
<i>they were more than intrigued
by the results.</i>

35:25.373 --> 35:30.544
This one was from 1632 to 1668.

35:30.628 --> 35:33.213
Whoa.

35:33.372 --> 35:34.881
It's purpose-built, right?

35:34.966 --> 35:36.466
- GARY: Yeah.
- CHARLES: Yeah.

35:36.625 --> 35:38.385
<i>NARRATOR:
Could it be possible</i>

35:38.544 --> 35:41.304
<i>that the team has now found
a similar kind of tool?</i>

35:41.389 --> 35:45.058
<i>If so, just what
was its purpose?</i>

35:45.217 --> 35:47.719
<i>And could it be connected
to the possible fragments</i>

35:47.812 --> 35:50.221
<i>of cargo barrels,
and evidence of a ship</i>

35:50.314 --> 35:53.224
<i>that have also recently
been unearthed</i>

35:53.309 --> 35:55.226
<i>in this region of the swamp?</i>

35:55.311 --> 35:56.644
It is.

35:56.737 --> 35:58.655
<i>GARY:
This is a shaped piece of wood,</i>

35:58.739 --> 36:02.400
<i>and obviously,
it had some kind of purpose.</i>

36:02.493 --> 36:06.404
And recovering pieces
of shaped wood is important

36:06.488 --> 36:09.749
because this area
is very close to the area

36:09.909 --> 36:13.837
where we recovered that piece
of ship's rail last year.

36:13.996 --> 36:16.006
BILLY:
We are getting closer and closer

36:16.165 --> 36:18.583
to, you know,
the swamp road, right?

36:18.667 --> 36:20.752
So, I mean,
it's a fair thought to think

36:20.845 --> 36:23.346
that the road was used
for a boat of some sort,

36:23.505 --> 36:25.173
and now we're just getting
in the good zone.

36:25.257 --> 36:28.009
- Yeah.
- We're finding a lot of pieces

36:28.093 --> 36:29.686
concentrated in one area.

36:29.845 --> 36:31.346
Hell of a lot
of interesting pieces, as well.

36:31.439 --> 36:33.765
- Yes.
- Yeah. I'd expect to find more.

36:33.858 --> 36:36.693
<i>GARY: I know Rick, Marty,
and Craig are gonna be</i>

36:36.852 --> 36:39.029
<i>- very interested in this piece.
- LAIRD: Yeah.</i>

36:43.025 --> 36:44.275
<i>- LAIRD: Hey, guys.
- ALEX: Hey, Laird.</i>

36:44.368 --> 36:45.610
-RICK: Here he is
-Three guys from the field.

36:45.703 --> 36:48.705
- Three guys from the swamp.
- What you got?

36:48.789 --> 36:51.282
Well, these are all coming out
from the same basic spot.

36:51.367 --> 36:53.877
<i>NARRATOR: After discovering
a number of wooden artifacts</i>

36:53.961 --> 36:58.122
<i>near the southern border
of the triangle-shaped swamp,</i>

36:58.216 --> 37:00.625
<i>archaeologist Laird Niven,
along with Scott Barlow</i>

37:00.718 --> 37:03.720
<i>and Billy Gerhardt,
have called a meeting</i>

37:03.804 --> 37:06.306
<i>with Rick, Marty, Craig
and other members of the team</i>

37:06.390 --> 37:09.142
<i>in the war room.</i>

37:09.227 --> 37:10.802
LAIRD:
This one is a bit of a mystery.

37:10.886 --> 37:12.896
Maybe as woodworking people,

37:13.055 --> 37:14.898
you'll have a little
more insight into it.

37:19.820 --> 37:22.405
- What the heck is that?
- Hmm.

37:22.564 --> 37:23.740
Hmm.

37:26.318 --> 37:29.746
(scoffs)
I have no idea what that is.

37:29.830 --> 37:31.498
When you first handed it,
I said,

37:31.582 --> 37:34.334
- part of a piece of furniture.
- Yup.

37:34.493 --> 37:36.995
No. You know, looks like
something must've that stained

37:37.088 --> 37:39.089
or something was around.

37:39.248 --> 37:40.590
Could a rope maybe
have done that?

37:40.749 --> 37:44.511
Yeah, it does almost look
like a rope rubbing on the...

37:44.670 --> 37:46.680
that one portion, under the lip.

37:46.839 --> 37:48.840
RICK: I'd say you're
right. That's a rope burn.

37:48.933 --> 37:50.258
- TOM: That's what I think it is. Yeah.
- RICK: Yeah.

37:50.351 --> 37:53.186
Yeah. That's quite possible.

37:53.271 --> 37:55.689
Then it's not furniture.
To me, that looks maritime.

37:55.848 --> 37:58.692
BILLY: It's all in the general
range of where we found, uh,

37:58.851 --> 38:00.277
the ship's rail last year.

38:00.361 --> 38:01.278
We're pretty darn close.

38:01.437 --> 38:03.280
<i>NARRATOR:
Could it be possible</i>

38:03.364 --> 38:06.357
<i>that what Gary Drayton,
Laird, Billy and Scott</i>

38:06.450 --> 38:09.703
<i>believed might be a tool
is actually another piece</i>

38:09.862 --> 38:11.204
<i>of a large sailing vessel?</i>

38:11.289 --> 38:13.623
It was used extensively,
that's for sure.

38:13.708 --> 38:16.376
Friction burn like that
is gonna take a while.

38:16.535 --> 38:18.369
Mm-hmm. I think that's a much
denser piece of wood...

38:18.462 --> 38:21.298
- BILLY: Yeah.
- Because it's-it's already dry.

38:21.457 --> 38:23.624
Yeah, so we talked
about C-14 dating,

38:23.709 --> 38:25.043
- but maybe we should look at...
- I think we should look

38:25.127 --> 38:27.220
- at species on that one.
- Yeah.

38:27.305 --> 38:28.555
'Cause if it is
some exotic species,

38:28.639 --> 38:30.390
that might tell us
something, too.

38:30.474 --> 38:31.975
Yeah, for sure.

38:32.134 --> 38:34.135
Well, we're kind of,
um, overwhelmed

38:34.219 --> 38:35.887
by the stuff coming out
of the swamp.

38:35.971 --> 38:37.305
You know, they used
to use black locust

38:37.398 --> 38:41.067
- or something really hard to-to wind ropes around.
- Yeah.

38:41.152 --> 38:42.310
<i>MARTY: You know,
they're pieces of wood.</i>

38:42.394 --> 38:43.978
<i>They're human-shaped.</i>

38:44.063 --> 38:45.897
<i>The swamp preserves them</i>

38:45.981 --> 38:47.490
<i>for literally hundreds of years.</i>

38:47.575 --> 38:49.159
So we need
to get everything tested

38:49.318 --> 38:52.236
to see how old the old is
and separate out the new.

38:52.330 --> 38:54.914
Anyway, the last one--
It's a worked piece of wood.

38:54.999 --> 38:58.418
Um, almost like it was meant
to be inserted partway.

